SIMPLE: whin
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whin
<hw>Whin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[W. <ets>chwyn</ets>
weeds, a single weed.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Gorse; furze. See
<er>Furze</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through the <qex>whins</qex>, and by the cairn.</q>
<rj><qau>Burns.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Woad-waxed.</def> <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Whinstone</er>.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Moor whin</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Petty
whin</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a low prickly shrub
(<spn>Genista Anglica</spn>) common in Western Europe.</cd> --
<col><b>Whin bruiser</b></col>, <cd>a machine for cutting and bruising
whin, or furze, to feed cattle on.</cd> -- <col><b>Whin
Sparrow</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the hedge sparrow.</cd>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Whin Thrush</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the redwing.</cd> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whinberry</ent>⟦br⟧
